This a filament cooling fan mount for the left nozzle of a Makerbot Replicator 2x. It will probably fit the Replcator 2 also.
It works fantastically and does not interfere with the movement of the carriage.
It is a redesign of a similar part I found on Thingiverse, however this one only cools the left nozzle as I only use the left nozzle to print PLA.
I have designed this part using SolidWorks and have included the original files should you want to make changes.
It is designed to fit standard 40mm radial fan like the ones used on the Replicators, (24V fans!)
I have printed it in ABS, then acetone bathed it to smooth it out.
The fan can be attached using 10mm M3 socket head screws and the mount can be attached to the x axis carriage using M3 screws, or zip ties.
I have run a set of wires for the fan from the 24V rail on the circuit board underneath, and placed a switch on the rear of my machine.
BTW anyone who has a Replicator 2x and has not flashed it with the latest version of the Sailfish Firmware (which can be found on Thingiverse https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:32084 ), I urge you to do so. It makes a HUGE difference to the performance of the machine and the quality of the prints.

description.text:
This is a needle cutter for an MPCNC Machine. This has 3mm holes in the face for 4 guide bearings. The brushless motor mounting pattern fits standard 16/19 self centering bolt patterns. The flywheel uses M3 screws and nuts to secure to a 3.17mm motor shaft. The holes in the face of the flywheel are 3mm that the threads of M3 screws will bite into. Both the flywheel face and the frame face have a 1mm extrusion to space the roller bearings. The Motor mount to face spacing accommodates 2212 brushless motors. The models are available in the Sketchup 3D warehouse for easy import and modification.

08 Oct 17
I just added two variations. Both are designed around the same motor and mount. One has extra guides at the top and one is shorter. Both are intneded to reduce the side slop of the needle flex as it makes it's rounds. Both work fine. There is a balance between wire length, speed of the rotation and stiffness of the wire that you have to play with to get the best results. On the shorter one, I am using .020" wire with great results. In the taller one with extra guides, .025" wire has worked well.

Another update/modification was to make the bearing hole slithly narrower and taller to work with the needle holder from moebeast's needle cutter. Again, there is a fine balance to find if you use that holder.

This project is stil active, so I am happy to receive your feedback and turn this work into something amazing.

I'm dreaming about creating lenses with 3d-printer, using SLA technology + polishing.
To make it more comfortable, I've designed this customizable file. This model seems quite ugly in the Customizer, so import it into OpenSCAD or just download.

File allows you to get spherical lens (both "+" and "-") based on thin lens approximation. You can set the following parameters:

  • Focal length;
  • Reflective index of material;
  • Lens diameter;
  • Edge thickness (for positive lens);
  • Will lens have plane surface or will be biconvex/biconcave with equal curvature.

As a designer it is difficult for me to develop such projects properly without having my own 3d-printer. Please give feedback to improve this design. Or tip me to see more cool projects).

Created hinge inserts so once both sides are connected these can be super glued on to create a complete hinge so objects don't separate after prolonged use.

Magic logo has been removed from the bottom of the box.

description.text: This is a filament guide, cleaner, and lubricator made for the Anet A8 stock extruder. This guide feeds directly into the stock extruder without the filament dragging on the side of the extruder inlet.

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2 mm

Infill:

20% or higher

Installation and Instructions

Parts needed:
-(2) - M4 x 12mm screws
-a sponge
-an appropriate lubricant for the type of filament you're using

Installation:
You will need M4 x 12mm to affix this to the extruder. Remove the two left most screws on the extruder carriage. Place the two M4 x 12mm screws in the holes that mount the guide to the carriage. Place the guide on the carriage and tighten screws finger tight. Look down the guide and line the bottom of the guide up with the filament inlet on the extruder. Once aligned to satisfaction, tighten down screws with a tool.

Instructions on use:
With scissors, cut the sponge to loosely fit in the top cup of the guide (it should barely stay inside the cup. Once fitted, cut the piece of sponge in half. Feed the filament through the top and then fit the sponge halves around the filament. Slide the top over the filament-sponge sandwich. Feed the filament into the bottom cup and then run the filament through the extruder like normally. Add a few drops of the appropriate lubricant for the filament into the top of the guide.

A remix of thingiverse part 2083254. That version with the holes in the base is far too wobbly vertically, and the motor mount printed on the hole bends far too easily from y axis belt tension. I'm also not a fan of vertically printed round holes. But I am a fan of moving the tension forces out to the threaded rods which completely eliminate using acrylic frame pieces for support.

This version adds a vertical brace to the motor mount, and changes the motor pulley hole to a hexagon, which print very nicely in a vertical orientation. Oh, and no holes in the base!

I presently have my version on my A8 and with full tension on my y axis belt, there is minimal deflection of the vertical support holding the motor plate. Any my rear acrylic plate is now flat again! Side benefit? The Y axis motor is a lot quieter too.
